<subSubSection id="C37F65649418FFC2BACF3BD0FB65FDB3" pageId="23" pageNumber="274" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BDA36EF9418FFC2BACF3BD0FB65FDB3" blockId="23.[151,1437,150,2042]" pageId="23" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis id="B911EAFD9418FFC2BACF3BD0FED5FE5F" bold="true" box="[199,328,474,501]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="274">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after Dr. Michael Geiser, 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D6C9418FFC2B9683BD1FC46FE5F" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[864,987,475,501]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
curator at The Natural History Museum in London, 
<collectingCountry id="F372767F9418FFC2BB113BF5FECFFDB3" box="[281,338,511,537]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="23" pageNumber="274">U.K.</collectingCountry>
, who collected specimens of the new species and kindly allowed me to study them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
